{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"leggy-heedless-mosquito","description":"# Tier-1 opportunistic detached drain + `rebar enrich` CLI\n\n## Why\nThe feature must run async across server/PC/Mac/cloud with ZERO client setup — no daemon, no broker, no scheduler. The proven pattern (git gc --auto, npm update-notifier) is to piggyback a cheap, detached drain on ordinary invocations. rebar already ships this exact mechanism for async push.\n\n## What\n- A `maybe_drain()` gate hung off ordinary rebar invocations: a cheap \"is-drain-needed?\" check that no-ops in the common case, then DETACHES the actual LLM enrichment to a child process that outlives the command — reusing the async-push pattern in `src/rebar/_store/push.py:108` (`Popen(start_new_session=True, close_fds=True, stdio=DEVNULL)` + the PYTHONPATH bootstrap).\n- The drainer: read soaked+unclaimed queue entries (S3), claim one, run the Cupid op (S1), write the digest (S2), mark done. Batch-cap tickets per run so a backlog can't stall a foreground command; lenient lock (skip silently if another drain holds it).\n- A `rebar enrich` CLI arm: `--drain` (process soaked entries, the detached target), and a status/`--once` mode for tests. Env opt-out (e.g. `REBAR_ENRICH_DISABLE`).\n\n## Scope\n- IN scope: the drain runner, the opportunistic gate + detach, the CLI arm, batch-cap, lenient lock, opt-out. Gracefully skips when [agents]/API key absent.\n- OUT of scope: native-scheduler registration (idea: Tier 2), CI drain (idea: Tier 3).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `rebar enrich --drain` processes all soaked, unclaimed queue entries (claim → extract → store digest → done), idempotently, then exits.\n- [ ] An ordinary rebar invocation opportunistically detaches a drain that survives parent exit and does NOT measurably slow the foreground command (cheap gate no-ops when nothing is soaked; work is detached).\n- [ ] Per-run batch cap bounds how many tickets one drain processes; a large backlog drains over several invocations without stalling any single one.\n- [ ] Concurrent drains do not double-process (lenient lock: a second drain finding the lock held skips silently, not errors).\n- [ ] With the `[agents]` extra / API key absent, the drain is a clean no-op (graceful skip).\n- [ ] `REBAR_ENRICH_DISABLE` (or equivalent) turns the opportunistic drain off entirely.","id":"c1de-d6a0-6cef-4135","parent_id":"bd83-c56f-1f72-4ef2","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Tier-1 opportunistic detached drain + `rebar enrich` CLI"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783568203244273001,"uuid":"1cb47695-c6ba-4d49-b949-0a20f81376ea"}